: pl. 29, fig. 1, 1a) and 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B73ACFF077406C17C" authority="Castro, 2005" authorityName="Castro" authorityYear="2005" box="[676,846,236,261]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="exophthalma" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B73ACFF077406C17C" box="[676,846,236,261]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. exophthalma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="87A4D5414E03B50B7250FF0774DFC17C" box="[856,919,236,261]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
(
<figureCitation id="36D8A8AD4E03B50B72A1FF07737AC17C" box="[937,1074,236,261]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="62.[113,124,1644,1661]" captionTargetBox="[103,1201,241,1584]" captionTargetId="figure-29@62.[70,1230,213,1607]" captionTargetPageId="62" captionText="FIG. 21. — Ethusina exophthalma n. sp., holotype cl 7.1 mm, cw 6.9 mm, Fiji, Bligh Water between Viti Levu and Vanua Levu islands, MUSORSTOM 10, stn CP 1331, 694-703 m (MNHN-B 28710); A, dorsal surface of carapace; B, ventral view of anterior portion of body; C, left G1, ventral view; D, left G2, ventral view. Scale bars: A, 5 mm; B, 2 mm; C, D, 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5399951" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5399951/files/figure.png" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Fig. 21A, B</figureCitation>
), where the basal antennal article is greatly expanded as in other members of the genus. Obviously, the eyes in these species are “mobile” when pushed by the use of needles or forceps because of their length. The same can be said about other species where the eye peduncles are relatively long and in species where in the males the eyes protrude beyond the outer orbital teeth, as in the case of 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B73ACFDE774E6C25C" authority="Chen, 1987" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1987" box="[676,942,524,549]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="longipes">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B73ACFDE77452C25C" box="[676,794,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. longipes</emphasis>
Chen, 1987
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B72C8FDE77597C23C" authority="Chen, 1993" authorityName="Chen" authorityYear="1993" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paralongipes">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B72C8FDE77321C25C" box="[960,1129,524,549]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. paralongipes</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B757BFDE77597C23C" author="CHEN H." pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="315 - 345" refId="ref76209" refString="CHEN H. 1993. - Crustacea Decapoda: Dorippidae of New Caledonia, Indonesia and the Philippines, in CROSNIER A. (ed.), Resultats des campagnes MUSORSTOM, volume 10. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle 156: 315 - 345." type="journal article" year="1993">Chen, 1993</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B7211FDC7736BC23C" authority="(Miers, 1886)" authorityName="Miers" authorityYear="1886" baseAuthorityName="Miers" baseAuthorityYear="1886" box="[793,1059,556,581]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="robusta">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B7211FDC774CBC23C" box="[793,899,556,581]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. robusta</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B7299FDC77353C23C" author="MIERS E. J." box="[913,1051,556,581]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="1 - 29" refId="ref78657" refString="MIERS E. J. 1886. - Report on the Brachyura collect- ed by H. M. S. Challenger during the years 1873 - 76, in Report on the Scientific Results of the Voyage of H. M. S. Challenger During the Years 1873 - 76 Under the Command of Captain George S. Nares, R. N., F. R. S. and the Late Captain Frank Tourle Thompson, R. N., Zoology 17 (49): I-L + 1 - 362, pls 1 - 29." type="book chapter" year="1886">Miers, 1886</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE5CB4284E03B50B73ACFDA7741BC3FC" blockId="47.[676,1210,204,1285]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">
The presence in 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B7267FDA775ADC2FC" authority="(Alcock, 1896)" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="desciscens">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B7267FDA77303C21C" box="[879,1099,588,613]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusina desciscens</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B7568FDA77595C2FC" author="ALCOCK A." pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="134 - 296" refId="ref75633" refString="ALCOCK A. 1896. - The Brachyura Oxystoma. Materials for a carcinological fauna of India, no. 2. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal 65 (pt 2, no. 2): 134 - 296, pls 6 - 8 (dated 1895, published 1896)." type="journal article" year="1896">Alcock, 1896</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
of eye peduncles that are relatively mobile was considered by 
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B728DFD677316C2DC" author="ALCOCK A." box="[901,1118,652,677]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" refId="ref75688" refString="ALCOCK A. 1899. - An Account of the Deep-Sea Brachyura Collected by the Royal Indian Marine Survey Ship Investigator. Indian Museum, Calcutta, iii + 85 + 2 p., 4 pls." type="book" year="1899">Alcock (1899: 35)</bibRefCitation>
as “the connecting-link between 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B72CAFD477343C2BC" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[962,1035,684,709]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B72CAFD477343C2BC" box="[962,1035,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B754FFD4773EEC2BC" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1884" box="[1095,1190,684,709]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B754FFD4773EEC2BC" box="[1095,1190,684,709]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
”. Such alleged mobility, however, was not noticed in any of the specimens of 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B72C5FD077303C37C" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[973,1099,748,773]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="desciscens">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B72C5FD077303C37C" box="[973,1099,748,773]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. desciscens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that were examined (see Remarks of 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B72DFFCE77314C35C" authorityName="" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[983,1116,780,805]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="desciscens">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B72DFFCE77314C35C" box="[983,1116,780,805]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">E. desciscens</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
below). Obviously, the apparent “mobility” of eye peduncles is also related to how long specimens have been fixed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AE5CB4284E03B50B73ACFC677495C57C" blockId="47.[676,1210,204,1285]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">
The allegedly ambiguous nature of 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B7534FC6773C0C3DC" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[1084,1160,908,933]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B7534FC6773C0C3DC" box="[1084,1160,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B73ACFC477447C3BC" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1884" box="[676,783,940,965]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B73ACFC477447C3BC" box="[676,783,940,965]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
led 
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B7244FC477348C3BC" author="ALCOCK A." box="[844,1024,940,965]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="134 - 296" refId="ref75633" refString="ALCOCK A. 1896. - The Brachyura Oxystoma. Materials for a carcinological fauna of India, no. 2. Journal of the Asiatic Society of Bengal 65 (pt 2, no. 2): 134 - 296, pls 6 - 8 (dated 1895, published 1896)." type="journal article" year="1896">Alcock (1896)</bibRefCitation>
and 
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B754DFC4774C9C39C" author="SERENE R. &amp; LOHAVANIJAYA P." pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="1 - 187" refId="ref80555" refString="SERENE R. &amp; LOHAVANIJAYA P. 1973. - The Brachyura (Crustacea: Decapoda) collected by the Naga Expedition, including a review of the Homolidae. Scientific results of marine investigations of the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand, 1959 - 1961. Naga Report 4 (4): 1 - 187." type="journal article" year="1973">Serène &amp; Lohavanijaya (1973)</bibRefCitation>
to consider 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B7509FC277316C39C" authorityName="Smith" authorityYear="1884" box="[1025,1118,972,997]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusina" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B7509FC277316C39C" box="[1025,1118,972,997]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as a junior synonym of 
<taxonomicName id="69E3CFAB4E03B50B725FFC0774EAC47C" baseAuthorityName="Alcock" baseAuthorityYear="1896" box="[855,930,1004,1029]" class="Malacostraca" family="Ethusidae" genus="Ethusa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9C97683A4E03B50B725FFC0774EAC47C" box="[855,930,1004,1029]" italics="true" pageId="47" pageNumber="546">Ethusa</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B72B9FC0775B9C45C" author="SERENE R. &amp; LOHAVANIJAYA P." pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="1 - 187" refId="ref80555" refString="SERENE R. &amp; LOHAVANIJAYA P. 1973. - The Brachyura (Crustacea: Decapoda) collected by the Naga Expedition, including a review of the Homolidae. Scientific results of marine investigations of the South China Sea and the Gulf of Thailand, 1959 - 1961. Naga Report 4 (4): 1 - 187." type="journal article" year="1973">Serène &amp; Lohavanijaya (1973)</bibRefCitation>
had a very limited amount of material at their disposal (only 
<specimenCount id="B8E57FA14E03B50B7298FBC77378C43C" box="[912,1072,1068,1093]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" type="generic">one specimen</specimenCount>
, which was misidentified) and they based their decision on the description and illustrations of the various species in the literature. The use of the relative mobility of the eyes as a character separating both genera also led 
<bibRefCitation id="CA72C9D94E03B50B73C3FB2774C1C49C" author="GORE R. H." box="[715,905,1228,1253]" pageId="47" pageNumber="546" pagination="200 - 217" refId="ref77176" refString="GORE R. H. 1983. - Notes on rare species of Munidopsis (Anomura: Galatheidae) and Ethusina (Brachyura: Dorippidae) collected by the USNS Bartlett in the Venezuela Basin, Caribbean Sea. Proceedings of the Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 135: 200 - 217." type="journal article" year="1983">Gore (1983: 211)</bibRefCitation>
to comment on the possible overlap between both genera.
</paragraph>
